#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><section><title>
#: debian-reference.en.xmlt:1450
msgid "Unix-like filesystem"
msgstr "Systme de fichiers de type Unix"

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><section><simpara>
#: debian-reference.en.xmlt:1451
msgid "In GNU/Linux and other <ulink url=\"&unixlike;\">Unix-like</ulink> operating systems, <ulink url=\"&files;\">files</ulink> are organized into <ulink url=\"&directories;\">directories</ulink>.  All files and directories are arranged in one big tree rooted at \"<literal>/</literal>\". It's called a tree because if you draw the filesystem, it looks like a tree but it is upside down."
msgstr "Avec GNU/Linux et d'autres systmes d'exploitation <ulink url=\"&unixlike;\">semblables  Unix</ulink>, les <ulink url=\"&files;\">fichiers</ulink> sont organiss en <ulink url=\"&directories;\">rpertoires</ulink>.  Tous les fichiers et les rpertoires sont disposs sous forme d'une grosse arborescence ancre sur &nbsp;<literal>/</literal>&nbsp;. On l'appelle un arbre parce que si vous dessinez le systme de fichiers, il ressemble  un arbre qui se trouverait dispos la tte en bas."

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><section><simpara>
#: debian-reference.en.xmlt:1452
msgid "These files and directories can be spread out over several devices. <literal>mount</literal>(8) serves to attach the filesystem found on some device to the big file tree.  Conversely, <literal>umount</literal>(8) detaches it again.  On recent Linux kernels, <literal>mount</literal>(8) with some options can bind part of a file tree somewhere else or can mount filesystem as shared, private, slave, or unbindable.  Supported mount options for each filesystem are available in \"<literal>/share/doc/linux-doc-2.6.*/Documentation/filesystems/</literal>\"."
msgstr "Ces fichiers et rpertoires peuvent tre rpartis sur plusieurs priphriques. La commande <literal>mount</literal>(8) sert  attacher les systmes de fichiers se trouvant sur certains priphriques  la grosse arborescence des fichiers.  l'oppos, la commande <literal>umount</literal>(8) les dtachera de nouveau. Avec les noyaux Linux rcents, <literal>mount</literal>(8) avec certaines options peut lier une partie d'une arborescence de fichiers  un autre emplacement ou peut monter un systme de fichier de manire partage, prive, esclave ou &nbsp;non-liable&nbsp;. Vous trouverez les options de montage prises en compte par chaque systme de fichiers dans &nbsp;<literal>/share/doc/linux-doc-2.6.*/Documentation/filesystems/</literal>&nbsp;."

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><section><simpara>
#: debian-reference.en.xmlt:1453
msgid "<emphasis role=\"strong\">Directories</emphasis> on Unix systems are called <emphasis role=\"strong\">folders</emphasis> on some other systems.  Please also note that there is no concept for <emphasis role=\"strong\">drive</emphasis> such as \"<literal>A:</literal>\" on any Unix system.  There is one filesystem, and everything is included. This is a huge advantage compared to Windows."
msgstr "Les <emphasis role=\"strong\">rpertoires</emphasis> d'un systme Unix sont appels <emphasis role=\"strong\">dossiers</emphasis> sur d'autres systmes. Vous remarquez aussi qu'il n'y a, sur aucun systme Unix, de concept de <emphasis role=\"strong\">lecteur</emphasis> tel que &nbsp;<literal>A:</literal>&nbsp;. Il y a un systme de fichier qui comprend tout. C'est un gros avantage compar  Windows."

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><section><section><title>
#: debian-reference.en.xmlt:1455
msgid "Unix file basics"
msgstr "Bases concernant les fichiers Unix"

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><section><section><simpara>
#: debian-reference.en.xmlt:1456
msgid "Here are some Unix file basics."
msgstr "Voici les bases des fichiers Unix&nbsp;:"

# type: Content of: <book><chapter><section><section><itemizedlist><listitem><simpara>
#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><section><section><itemizedlist><listitem><simpara>
#: debian-reference.en.xmlt:1460
msgid "Filenames are <emphasis role=\"strong\">case sensitive</emphasis>.  That is, \"<literal>MYFILE</literal>\" and \"<literal>MyFile</literal>\" are different files."
msgstr "les noms de fichiers sont <emphasis role=\"strong\">sensibles  la casse</emphasis>. Ce qui veut dire que &nbsp;<literal>MONFICHIER</literal>&nbsp; et &nbsp;<literal>MonFichier</literal>&nbsp; sont des fichiers diffrents&nbsp;;"

# type: Content of: <book><chapter><section><section><itemizedlist><listitem><simpara>
#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><section><section><itemizedlist><listitem><simpara>
#: debian-reference.en.xmlt:1465
msgid "The <emphasis role=\"strong\">root directory</emphasis> means root of the filesystem referred as simply \"<literal>/</literal>\".  Don't confuse this with the home directory for the root user: \"<literal>/root</literal>\"."
msgstr "on se rfre au <emphasis role=\"strong\">rpertoire racine</emphasis> (&nbsp;root directory&nbsp;) qui est la racine du systme de fichiers simplement par &nbsp;<literal>/</literal>&nbsp;. Ne pas le confondre avec le rpertoire personnel de l'utilisateur root: &nbsp;<literal>/root</literal>&nbsp;&nbsp;;"

# type: Content of: <book><chapter><section><section><itemizedlist><listitem><simpara>
#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><section><section><itemizedlist><listitem><simpara>
#: debian-reference.en.xmlt:1470
msgid "Every directory has a name which can contain any letters or symbols <emphasis role=\"strong\">except \"<literal>/</literal>\"</emphasis>.  The root directory is an exception; its name is \"<literal>/</literal>\" (pronounced \"slash\" or \"the root directory\") and it cannot be renamed."
msgstr "un nom de rpertoire peut tre constitu de n'importe quelle lettre ou symbole <emphasis role=\"strong\">sauf &nbsp;<literal>/</literal>&nbsp;</emphasis>. Le rpertoire racine est une exception, son nom est &nbsp;<literal>/</literal>  (prononc &nbsp;slash&nbsp; ou &nbsp;le rpertoire root&nbsp;), il ne peut pas tre renomm&nbsp;;"

# type: Content of: <book><chapter><section><section><itemizedlist><listitem><simpara>
#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><section><section><itemizedlist><listitem><simpara>
#: debian-reference.en.xmlt:1475
msgid "Each file or directory is designated by a <emphasis role=\"strong\">fully-qualified filename</emphasis>, <emphasis role=\"strong\">absolute filename</emphasis>, or <emphasis role=\"strong\">path</emphasis>, giving the sequence of directories which must be passed through to reach it.  The three terms are synonymous."
msgstr "chaque fichier ou rpertoire est dsign par un <emphasis role=\"strong\">nom de fichier entirement qualifi</emphasis>, <emphasis role=\"strong\">nom de fichier absolu</emphasis> ou <emphasis role=\"strong\">chemin</emphasis>, indiquant la squence de rpertoires que l'on doit traverser pour l'atteindre. Les trois expressions sont synonymes&nbsp;;"

# type: Content of: <book><chapter><section><section><itemizedlist><listitem><simpara>
#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><section><section><itemizedlist><listitem><simpara>
#: debian-reference.en.xmlt:1480
msgid "All <emphasis role=\"strong\">fully-qualified filenames</emphasis> begin with the \"<literal>/</literal>\" directory, and there's a \"<literal>/</literal>\" between each directory or file in the filename.  The first \"<literal>/</literal>\" is the top level directory, and the other \"<literal>/</literal>\"'s separate successive subdirectories, until we reach the last entry which is the name of the actual file.  The words used here can be confusing.  Take the following <emphasis role=\"strong\">fully-qualified filename</emphasis> as an example: \"<literal>/usr/share/keytables/us.map.gz</literal>\".  However, people also refers to its basename \"<literal>us.map.gz</literal>\" alone as a filename."
msgstr "tous les <emphasis role=\"strong\">noms de fichiers entirement qualifis</emphasis> commencent par le rpertoire &nbsp;<literal>/</literal>&nbsp; et il y a un <literal>/</literal>&nbsp; entre chaque rpertoire ou fichier dans le nom du fichier. Le premier &nbsp;<literal>/</literal>&nbsp; est le rpertoire de plus haut niveau, et les autres &nbsp;<literal>/</literal>&nbsp; sparent les sous-rpertoires successifs jusqu' ce que l'on atteigne la dernire entre qui est le nom fichier proprement dit. Les mots utiliss ici peuvent tre source de confusion. Prenez comme exemple le <emphasis role=\"strong\">nom pleinement qualifi</emphasis> suivant&nbsp;: &nbsp;<literal>/usr/share/keytables/us.map.gz</literal>&nbsp;. Cependant, les gens utiliseront souvent son nom de base &nbsp;<literal>us.map.gz</literal>&nbsp; seul comme nom de fichier&nbsp;;"

# type: Content of: <book><chapter><section><section><itemizedlist><listitem><simpara>
#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><section><section><itemizedlist><listitem><simpara>
#: debian-reference.en.xmlt:1485
msgid "The root directory has a number of branches, such as \"<literal>/etc/</literal>\" and \"<literal>/usr/</literal>\".  These subdirectories in turn branch into still more subdirectories, such as \"<literal>/etc/init.d/</literal>\" and \"<literal>/usr/local/</literal>\".  The whole thing viewed collectively is called the <emphasis role=\"strong\">directory tree</emphasis>.  You can think of an absolute filename as a route from the base of the tree (\"<literal>/</literal>\") to the end of some branch (a file).  You also hear people talk about the directory tree as if it were a <emphasis role=\"strong\">family</emphasis> tree: thus subdirectories have <emphasis role=\"strong\">parents</emphasis>, and a path shows the complete ancestry of a file.  There are also relative paths that begin somewhere other than the root directory.  You should remember that the directory \"<literal>../</literal>\" refers to the parent directory.  This terminology also applies to other directory like structures, such as hierarchical data structures."
msgstr "le rpertoire racine comporte de nombreuses branches, telles que &nbsp;<literal>/etc/</literal>&nbsp; et &nbsp;<literal>/usr/</literal>&nbsp;. Ces sous-rpertoires se dcomposent eux-mmes en d'autres sous-rpertoires comme &nbsp;<literal>/etc/ init.d/</literal>&nbsp; et &nbsp;<literal>/usr/local/</literal>&nbsp;. Lensemble de la chose, vu globalement, s'appelle l'<emphasis role=\"strong\">arborescence des rpertoires</emphasis>.  Vous pouvez imaginer un nom de fichier absolu comme une route partant de la base de l'arbre (&nbsp;<literal>/</literal>&nbsp;) jusqu' l'extrmit de certaines branches (le fichier). Vous entendrez aussi certains parler de l'arborescence des rpertoire comme d'un arbre <emphasis role=\"strong\">gnalogique</emphasis>&nbsp;: les sous-rpertoires ont alors des <emphasis role=\"strong\">parents</emphasis> et un chemin montre l'ascendance complte d'un fichier. Il y a aussi des chemins relatifs qui commencent quelque part ailleurs qu'au niveau du rpertoire racine. Il faut vous souvenir que le rpertoire &nbsp;<literal>../</literal>&nbsp; indique le rpertoire parent. Cette terminologie s'applique de la mme manire aux autre structures ressemblant aux rpertoires comme les structures de donnes hirarchiques&nbsp;;"

# type: Content of: <book><chapter><section><section><itemizedlist><listitem><simpara>
#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><section><section><itemizedlist><listitem><simpara>
#: debian-reference.en.xmlt:1490
msgid "There's no special directory path name component that corresponds to a physical device, such as your hard disk.  This differs from <ulink url=\"&rtbb;\">RT-11</ulink>, <ulink url=\"&cpm;\">CP/M</ulink>, <ulink url=\"&openvms;\">OpenVMS</ulink>, <ulink url=\"&msdos;\">MS-DOS</ulink>, <ulink url=\"&amigaos;\">AmigaOS</ulink>, and <ulink url=\"&microsoftwindows;\">Microsoft Windows</ulink>, where the path contains a device name such as \"<literal>C:\\</literal>\".  (However, directory entries do exist that refer to physical devices as a part of the normal filesystem.  See <xref linkend=\"_filesystem_internals\"/>.)"
msgstr "il n'y a pas de chemin de rpertoire spcial correspondant  un priphrique physique tel que votre disque dur. Ceci est diffrent de <ulink url=\"&rtbb;\">RT-11</ulink>, <ulink url=\"&cpm;\">CP/M</ulink>, <ulink url=\"&openvms;\">OpenVMS</ulink>, <ulink url=\"&msdos;\">MS-DOS</ulink>, <ulink url=\"&amigaos;\">AmigaOS</ulink> et <ulink url=\"&microsoftwindows;\">Microsoft Windows</ulink>, o le chemin comporte le nom du priphrique comme &nbsp;<literal>C:\\</literal>&nbsp;. (Il existe cependant des entres de rpertoire qui font rfrence aux priphriques physique en tant qu'lment du systme de fichiers normal. Voir <xref linkend=\"_filesystem_internals\"/>)."

# type: Content of: <book><chapter><section><section><note><simpara>
#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><section><section><note><simpara>
#: debian-reference.en.xmlt:1495
msgid "While you <emphasis role=\"strong\">can</emphasis> use almost any letters or symbols in a file name, in practice it is a bad idea to do so.  It is better to avoid any characters that often have special meanings on the command line, including spaces, tabs, newlines, and other special characters: <literal>{ } ( ) [ ] ' ` \" \\ / &gt; &lt; | ; ! # &amp; ^ * % @ $</literal> .  If you want to separate words in a name, good choices are the period, hyphen, and underscore.  You could also capitalize each word, \"<literal>LikeThis</literal>\". Experienced Linux users tend to avoid spaces in filenames."
msgstr "Bien que vous <emphasis role=\"strong\">puissiez</emphasis> utiliser la plupart des lettres ou symboles dans un nom de fichier, c'est en pratique un mauvaise ide de le faire. Il est prfrable d'viter tous les caractres qui ont une signification particulire sur la ligne de commande, comme les espaces, tabulations, sauts de ligne, et autres caractres spciaux&nbsp;: <literal>{ } ( ) [ ] ' ` \" \\ / &gt; &lt; | ; ! # &amp; ^ * % @ $</literal>.  Si vous voulez sparer des mots dans un nom, de bons choix sont le point, le tiret et le tiret soulign. Vous pouvez aussi mettre une majuscule en tte de chaque mot &nbsp;<literal>CommeCeci</literal>&nbsp;. Les utilisateurs Linux expriments on tendance  aussi  viter les espaces dans les noms de fichiers."

# type: Content of: <book><chapter><section><section><note><simpara>
#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><section><section><note><simpara>
#: debian-reference.en.xmlt:1498
msgid "The word \"root\" can mean either \"root user\" or \"root directory\".  The context of their usage should make it clear."
msgstr "Le mot &nbsp;root&nbsp; signifie soit &nbsp;utilisateur root&nbsp;, soit &nbsp;rpertoire root&nbsp; Le contexte de sont utilisation devrait permettre de les distinguer."

# type: Content of: <book><chapter><section><section><note><simpara>
#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><section><section><note><simpara>
#: debian-reference.en.xmlt:1501
msgid "The word <emphasis role=\"strong\">path</emphasis> is used not only for <emphasis role=\"strong\">fully-qualified filename</emphasis> as above but also for the <emphasis role=\"strong\">command search path</emphasis>.  The intended meaning is usually clear from the context."
msgstr "Le mot <emphasis role=\"strong\">chemin</emphasis> (&nbsp;path&nbsp;) nest pas utilis que pour <emphasis role=\"strong\">noms de fichiers entirement qualifis </emphasis> comme ci-dessus mais aussi pour le <emphasis role=\"strong\"> chemin de recherche des commandes</emphasis>.  La signification voulue est habituellement claire selon le contexte."

#. type: Content of: <book><chapter><section><section><simpara>
#: debian-reference.en.xmlt:1503
